class MyHashSet {
    constructor() {
        this.size = 1000;
        this.set = new Array(this.size).fill(null).map(() => []);
    }

    hash(key) {
        return key % this.size;
    }

    add(key) {
        let idx = this.hash(key);
        let bucket = this.set[idx];

        if (!bucket.includes(key)) {
            bucket.push(key);
        }
    }

    contains(key) {
        let idx = this.hash(key);
        return this.set[idx].includes(key);
    }

    remove(key) {
        let idx = this.hash(key);
        let bucket = this.set[idx];

        let index = bucket.indexOf(key);
        if (index !== -1) {
            bucket.splice(index, 1);
        }
    }
}



Pattern-
Hashing + Buckets (Separate Chaining)
  
Key Idea-
Use an array of buckets
Each bucket stores keys
Use a hash function to map key → index
  
Hash Function-
index = key % size
  
Data Structure-
Array of lists
Each list stores unique keys
  
Operations-
add(key):
Find bucket using hash
If key not present → insert
  
contains(key):
Find bucket
Return true if key exists, else false
  
remove(key):
Find bucket
Remove key if present
  
Steps-
1. Initialize array with empty lists
2. For each operation:
 - Compute index using hash
 - Perform operation in that bucket
  
Complexity-
Time:
add: O(1) average
contains: O(1) average
remove: O(1) average
Worst Case:
O(n) (all keys in same bucket)
  
Final Rule-
Map keys to indices using hash function
Handle collisions using buckets
Ensure no duplicate keys stored

